  "prompt": "Are there any satellites recovered from space?",
  "response": "Yes, several satellites have been recovered from space throughout history:\n\n1. Corona Spy Satellites (USA)\n- Recovered film-based reconnaissance satellites\n- Operational from 1959-1972\n- Capsules were recovered mid-air by aircraft\n\n2. Zond Satellites (Soviet Union)\n- Lunar reconnaissance and return missions\n- Some capsules successfully returned to Earth in the 1960s\n\n3. Genesis Solar Wind Sample Return Mission (NASA)\n- Launched in 2001\n- Collected solar wind particles\n- Crashed in Utah in 2004 but some samples were recovered\n\n4. Hayabusa Missions (Japan)\n- Asteroid sample return missions\n- Hayabusa (2003) and Hayabusa2 (2014) successfully returned asteroid samples to Earth\n\n5. Biosatellite Missions (Various Countries)\n- Carried living organisms for scientific research\n- Some missions returned biological samples\n\n6. Some Chinese recoverable satellites\n- Have conducted multiple missions returning scientific payloads\n\nMost modern satellites are not designed for recovery and typically burn up in the atmosphere or remain in orbit. Recovery missions are complex and expensive, so they are relatively rare.",
